<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-12T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-12T12:00:00-05:00" n="862" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d862">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/9158</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Christiania</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-12T18:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 12, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 13, 12.50
                                a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>581. The following official announcement appeared in the press this
                            morning: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>The German Minister in Christiania has informed the Foreign
                                    Office that owing to previous British declarations that the
                                    North Sea is a war zone<note n="1" xml:id="d862fn1">
                                        <ref target="frus1914Supp#pg_464">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914,
                                            Supplement, p. 464</ref>.</note> and the German Bay
                                    (Heligoland [Bight]) a danger zone,<note n="2" xml:id="d862fn2">
                                        <ref target="frus1917Supp01v01#pg_518">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1917, Supplement 1, pp.
                                            518</ref>–<ref target="frus1917Supp01v01#pg_519">519</ref> and <ref target="frus1917Supp01v01#pg_520">520</ref>.</note> the Imperial German Government is
                                    obliged, in order to meet the situation created by the said
                                    declarations, to proceed to the extraordinary measure of warning
                                    neutral ships against navigating in the German Bay and against
                                    further dangers to which it becomes necessary to expose neutral
                                    ships in consequence of British warfare in this zone. The danger
                                    of navigating in this zone can only be avoided by following
                                    special directions which can be obtained from the German naval
                                    authorities.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Schmedeman</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>